{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506690","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506690"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:45:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:45:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2558"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2558","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2558"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.19,0.38,0.4,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2558"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52612"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2558","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2558"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2558"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37974"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2626"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3373"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13671"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14929"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43188"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52612","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52612"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic one day after undergoing a right renal biopsy for investigation of refractory hypertension and proteinuria. He reports blood in his urine since the procedure but denies any clots, dysuria or frequency. He has some right flank pain at the biopsy site but otherwise feels well. He has a medical history of hypertension. His only regular medication is amlodipine. He does not smoke and drinks alcohol occasionally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 75/min, blood pressure 140/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Abdominal examination reveals a soft abdomen with minor right flank tenderness. There is no swelling or erythema around the biopsy site. He provides a light pink stained urine sample with no evident clots. His most recent haemoglobin today is 109 g/L (135-180), down from 112 g/L yesterday.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence empirical antibiotics","Perform a urine dipstick","Ultrasound the renal tract","Ensure adequate hydration","Organise a blood transfusion"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with minor complications following a renal biopsy, including macroscopic haematuria and mild flank pain. These are common and generally benign post-biopsy findings, especially within the first 24-48 hours after the procedure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnsuring adequate hydration\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in management. Adequate hydration is important post renal biopsy and may help with haematuria. It promotes urine flow, which can help flush out any minor bleeding and prevent clot formation. This conservative approach is suitable for patients with minor, expected post-biopsy complications who are otherwise stable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing empirical antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this case. The patient shows no signs of infection (no fever, no dysuria, no frequency) and prophylactic antibiotics are not routinely given after renal biopsies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerforming a urine dipstick\u003C/strong\u003E would not provide significant additional information in this case. The haematuria is already macroscopically evident, and there are no signs suggesting a urinary tract infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound of the renal tract\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary at this stage. It would be indicated if there were signs of severe bleeding, such as significant haemoglobin drop, haemodynamic instability, or suspicion of a large perinephric haematoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrganising a blood transfusion\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for this patient. His haemoglobin has only dropped slightly (3 g/L) and he is haemodynamically stable. Blood transfusions are reserved for cases of severe bleeding with significant haemoglobin drops or haemodynamic instability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key in managing post-biopsy patients is to differentiate between minor, expected complications and more serious ones requiring immediate intervention. In this case, the patient\u0027s symptoms are consistent with minor, expected post-biopsy changes. However, he should be advised to seek immediate medical attention if he develops severe pain, large clots in the urine, inability to urinate, fever, or signs of significant blood loss (dizziness, pallor, tachycardia).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bleeding is an important complication post renal biopsy, with macroscopic haematuria affecting 3-9% of cases.","Minor haematuria, mild pain around the biopsy site, and a slight drop in haemoglobin can be tolerated in the first 24-48 hours post-biopsy.","Adequate hydration is important post renal biopsy and may help with haematuria."],"references":["Ramos Botelho Antunes P, Almeida Ara\u00fajo S, Maria Carvalho Miranda S, Franco Monteiro Prado F, Felipe Fran\u00e7a Antunes L, et al. Post-Biopsy Complications Associated with Percutaneous Kidney Biopsy. Renal Diseases. IntechOpen; 2020. Available at: http://dx.doi.org/10.5772/intechopen.89226","Trajceska L, Severova-Andreevska G, Dzekova-Vidimliski P, et al. Complications and Risks of Percutaneous Renal Biopsy. Open Access Maced J Med Sci. 2019;7(6):992-995. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6454172/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37974"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2558"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37974","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37974"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-07T15:36:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-07T15:38:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2558"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52612"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGrou